                                "start": 0,
                                "stop": 9.873,
                                "byte_start": 84218,
                                "byte_stop": 123715,
                                "text": "The opinion of the Court in No. 98-2043, Hunt-Wesson, Inc. versus Franchise Tax Board of California will be announced by Justice Breyer."
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    {
                        "start": 9.873,
                        "stop": 195.526,
                        "byte_start": 123715,
                        "byte_stop": 0,
                        "speaker": {
                            "ID": 15139,
                            "name": "Stephen G. Breyer",
                            "href": "https:\/\/api.oyez.org\/people\/stephen_g_breyer",
                            "last_name": "Breyer",
                            "roles": [
                                {
                                    "id": 2785,
                                    "type": "scotus_justice",
                                    "date_start": 775890000,
                                    "date_end": 0,
                                    "appointing_president": "Bill Clinton",
                                    "role_title": "Associate Justice of the Supreme Court of the United States",
                                    "institution_name": "Supreme Court of the United States",
                                    "href": "https:\/\/api.oyez.org\/preson_role\/scotus_justice\/2785"
                                }
                            ],
                            "thumbnail": {
                                "id": 32682,
                                "mime": "image\/png",
                                "size": 49908,
                                "href": "https:\/\/api.oyez.org\/sites\/default\/files\/stephen_g_breyer_0.png"
                            },
                            "length_of_service": 7777,
                            "identifier": "stephen_g_breyer"
                        },
                        "text_blocks": [
                            {
                                "start": 9.873,
                                "stop": 36.19,
                                "byte_start": 123715,
                                "byte_stop": 229041,
                                "text": "The Federal Constitution permits a state to tax a propionate share of the income of an out of state company that does a particular business both inside and outside the State, but the state cannot tax income that that kind of company receives from an out-of-state unrelated business activity that constitutes a discrete business entity."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 36.19,
                                "stop": 59.317,
                                "byte_start": 229041,
                                "byte_stop": 321514,
                                "text": "So, imagine an Illinois tin can maker that does a $10 million tin can business in every state and suppose that company also has $200,000 dividend income from a completely unrelated New Zealand sheep farm; that means California could tax its share of the tin can income but it could not touch that $200,000 dividend."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 59.317,
                                "stop": 61.942,
                                "byte_start": 321514,
                                "byte_stop": 332068,
                                "text": "Now what has California done?"
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 61.942,
                                "stop": 74.382,
                                "byte_start": 332068,
                                "byte_stop": 381805,
                                "text": "Well, their system permits the manufacturer to deduct certain cost from income including interest cost; say they produce those tin cans with borrowed money in part."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 74.382,
                                "stop": 99.639,
                                "byte_start": 381805,
                                "byte_stop": 482847,
                                "text": "Well, California says that you can deduct that interest only to the extent that it exceeds the dividend from the sheep farm, so if the company let us say has $300,000 in tin can interest cost, it could not deduct the $300,000, they could only deduct $100,000 because it exceeds the $200,000 dividend by $100,000."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 99.639,
                                "stop": 108.14,
                                "byte_start": 482847,
                                "byte_stop": 516806,
                                "text": "Now, does the Constitution permit the type of deduction system that I just illustrated with this example which is a made up example?"
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 108.14,
                                "stop": 120.957,
                                "byte_start": 516806,
                                "byte_stop": 568110,
                                "text": "We decide that it does not, we think that California\u2019s deduction rule simply taxes in out of state companies non-unitary income, the vary income that the Constitution places outside the state\u0027s taxing power."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 120.957,
                                "stop": 134.908,
                                "byte_start": 568110,
                                "byte_stop": 623908,
                                "text": "Some years ago this Court wrote effectively that a tax on sleeping that is measured by the number of shoes in your closet is not a tax on sleeping, it is a tax on shoes and that basically underlies our reasoning in this case."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 134.908,
                                "stop": 152.042,
                                "byte_start": 623908,
                                "byte_stop": 692453,
                                "text": "Now, California points out that it is difficult to know if the borrowed money is really for the sheep business or for the tin can business and that is a good point, but it does not justify a rule that assumes that all borrowings are really for sheep."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 152.042,
                                "stop": 168.719,
                                "byte_start": 692453,
                                "byte_stop": 759118,
                                "text": "Neither the Federal Government nor any state makes any assumption that is that reckoning, rather every other jurisdiction uses a tracing rule, assumptions or allocates borrowings between taxable and non-taxable sources in some proportionate way."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 168.719,
                                "stop": 173.619,
                                "byte_start": 759118,
                                "byte_stop": 778762,
                                "text": "California has not explained why it could not do the same."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 173.619,
                                "stop": 180.023,
                                "byte_start": 778762,
                                "byte_stop": 804362,
                                "text": "For that reason California\u2019s system in our view does not reflect the reasonable sense of how income is generated."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 180.023,
                                "stop": 189.245,
                                "byte_start": 804362,
                                "byte_stop": 841247,
                                "text": "It is therefore not justified and because it taxes untaxable income the Due Process and Commerce Clauses of the Federal Constitution forbid it."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 189.245,
                                "stop": 193.266,
                                "byte_start": 841247,
                                "byte_stop": 857338,
                                "text": "The lower court decision upholding California\u2019s deduction rule is reversed."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 193.266,
                                "stop": 195.526,
                                "byte_start": 857338,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "Our decision is unanimous."
                            }
                        ]
                    }
                ]
